    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I couldn't resist bringing up the goblins, couldn't I? Anyway, back to the science!\n\nThe inclination of the orbit does play a role in how close planets appear to be when in conjunction. Think of it like a game of cosmic billiards - the angles of the orbits can affect the trajectory of the planets as they approach each other.\n\nWhen two planets are in close conjunction, their orbits are essentially \"colliding\" in the sky. If one planet's orbit is highly inclined relative to the other, it can cause them to appear farther apart than they actually are. This is because the inclined orbit creates a \"shadow\" effect, where the planet appears to be hiding behind a \"hill\" of its own orbit.\n\nFor example, if Jupiter's orbit is tilted about 1 degree relative to the plane of the solar system, its conjunction with a nearby planet like Mars might appear more like a close opposition (when two planets are on the same side of the Sun) than a true conjunction. The inclination of the orbit can make the planets appear more like distant, separated objects, rather than close together.\n\nOn the other hand, if the inclination is minimal (like 0.1 degrees), the planets will appear closer together, and the",
